"response_text": "The mean percentage difference between maximum and minimum choice function scores commences at 0.0000 at the start of the simulation. Throughout the 32 time steps, the metric demonstrates a persistent and significant upward trend, concluding at a value of 0.7508. This progression indicates a substantial increase in the heterogeneity of agent evaluations over time. Statistical analysis confirms the robustness of this increase, with rolling Mann-Kendall tests yielding a tau of 1.000 across all windows, signifying a strong monotonic growth.\n\nThe trajectory is characterized by specific shifts in momentum, identified by inflection points at time steps 7, 12, and 28. Between these points, the rate of divergence fluctuates, accompanied by localized oscillations observed between time steps 6 and 10, 16 and 19, and 26 and 30. These fluctuations suggest intermittent periods where individual agent scores adjust rapidly before settling into the broader trend of divergence. Contextually, the initial value of zero reflects the standardized initialization of agent perceptions regarding milk choices. The rise to 0.7508 illustrates the impact of model mechanics such as habit strength, social conformity, and susceptibility to norms. As agents navigate the network and incorporate health and environmental signals, their individual choice functions differentiate, mirroring the real-world development of diverse consumer preferences from a uniform baseline."
}

